article.headline: CS Bakersfield 73, S. Dakota St. 71
article.story: BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) -- Cal State Bakersfield overcame a late six-point deficit to upend South Dakota State in overtime, 73-71 Friday night. SDSU (5-7) led 61-56 with five minutes remaining when senior center Ben Beran knocked down a 17-foot jumper for the last of his game-high 25 points. But Zack Grasmick drilled a pair of three-pointers as Bakersfield (3-10) closed regulation on a 9-3 run to force the extra period. The game was every bit as close as the final score indicated, with the teams -- both former NCAA Division II men's basketball powers -- playing through 12 ties and 13 lead changes. SDSU nearly forced a second overtime, but Garrett Callahan's 15-foot jumper circled the rim and came back out as time expired. Sophomore forward Trent Blakley posted career highs of 23 points and nine rebounds to lead CSUB to its second consecutive victory. Blakley saved his best for when it counted most, grabbing a defensive rebound then knocking down a pair of free throws with 1:05 remaining in regulation to force overtime. With CSUB clinging to a two-point, 69-67 lead late in overtime, he grabbed his fifth offensive rebound then made two more free throws to give Bakersfield a 73-69 lead it would not relinquish. Beran led all scorers for SDSU with 25 points on 11-of-16 shooting. The game marks the first time the Roadrunners have won consecutive games as an NCAA Division I program.
